@startuml PostApiSolutionParallel

title Idempotent POST Solution - Parallel Request Case (Atomic Key Claim)

skinparam backgroundColor #FAFAFA
skinparam ArrowColor #555555
skinparam NoteBackgroundColor #FFFDE7
skinparam NoteBorderColor #F9A825

autonumber

actor "Browser Tab 1" as tab1
actor "Browser Tab 2" as tab2
participant "API Service" as api
database "Idempotency\nKey Store" as keyStore
database "Orders DB" as db

== Same User sends same request with same UUID from 2 browser tabs ==
par Tab 1: POST with UUID=abc123
  tab1 -> api : POST /orders\nIdempotency-Key: abc123\n(body: item=A, qty=1)
  api -> api : Check header present
else Tab 2: POST with UUID=abc123
  tab2 -> api : POST /orders\nIdempotency-Key: abc123\n(body: item=A, qty=1)
  api -> api : Check header present
end

note right of api
Both requests have same Idempotency-Key.
Now using ATOMIC operations to prevent
duplicates despite race condition.
end note

== CRITICAL SECTION: Acquire Lock before key insert ==
note over api
  Mutex Lock / Synchronized Block
  Only ONE thread allowed at a time.
  Other threads WAIT at the lock boundary.
end note

api -> api : ACQUIRE LOCK\n(ReentrantLock / synchronized block\nor DB SELECT FOR UPDATE)

note right of api
  Thread safety:
  Tab 1 acquires lock first.
  Tab 2 blocks and waits.
end note

par Tab 1 Claim (lock owner)
  api -> keyStore : INSERT idempotency_key=abc123\nstatus='CREATED'\n(UNIQUE constraint)
  keyStore -> api : OK - Key claimed by Tab 1
  api -> api : RELEASE LOCK\n(Tab 2 now unblocked)
else Tab 2 Claim (was blocked, now enters)
  api -> keyStore : INSERT idempotency_key=abc123\nstatus='CREATED'\n(UNIQUE constraint)
  keyStore -> api : CONSTRAINT VIOLATION\n(Key already exists!)
  api -> api : RELEASE LOCK
end

note right of keyStore
  Two-layer protection:
  1. Mutex Lock: serializes thread access
  2. DB UNIQUE constraint: final safety net
  Only ONE request can insert the key.
end note

== Tab 1: Process (key owner) ==
api -> db : INSERT order (item=A, qty=1)
db -> api : OK (order_id=501)
api -> keyStore : UPDATE status='CONSUMED'\nstored_response={order_id:501, code:201}
keyStore -> api : OK
api -> tab1 : HTTP 201 Created\n{order_id: 501}

== Tab 2: Handle conflict ==
api -> keyStore : SELECT status WHERE\nidempotency_key=abc123
keyStore -> api : status='CREATED'\n(still processing)
api -> tab2 : HTTP 409 Conflict\nor wait/retry with exponential backoff

note bottom
OUTCOME:
Tab 1: Gets order_id=501
Tab 2: Gets HTTP 409 Conflict (request rejected)
OR Tab 2 can retry and get cached response
once Tab 1 marks status='CONSUMED'

Result: No duplicate order created!
Only one order exists.
end note

@enduml

